<table bgcolor="#FFFFFF" width="95%" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" border="0"><tr><td width="10"><img width="10" height="1" src="images/space.gif" alt=""></td><td width="100%"><!-- spacer -->

<table cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" border="0" bgcolor=""  width="95%" align="center"><tr><td>
<table cellpadding="4" cellspacing="1" border="0"  width="100%">
<tr>
	<td bgcolor="#DEDFDF" width="175" valign="top" nowrap>
	<a name="post66566"></a>
	
	<font size="2" face="Verdana, Arial"><b>Serrath</b></font><br>
	<font size="1" face="Verdana, Arial">Cleric</font><br>
	<p>
	<font size="1" face="Verdana, Arial">Registered: Jul 2002<br>
	Location: Waterloo, ON, Canada<br>
	Posts: 29</font></td>
	
	<td bgcolor="#DEDFDF" width="100%" valign="top">
	<font size="1" face="Verdana, Arial"><img src="../ubb/icons/icon1.gif" alt="Post" border="0"> <b></b></font>
	<p><font size="2" face="Verdana, Arial">short answer, it depends on the mob. different mobs have different aggro calculations (commonly called 'intelligence'). Giants, for example, take into account how close PC's are a lot more then snakes. velius mobs seem to hate sitting characters more then luclin mobs and dragons cast so much tank usually have no problems maintaining aggro ^_^<br />
anyway, on mobs like Vindi, AoW, Tormax or the rest of the giant clan cleric placement seems more important then the timing of the CH rotation. its important to stand as far away from the giant as possible before starting the rotation. we also generally start the rotation so the mob is still incoming, that way when the first heal lands it doesn't heal for as much as thus doesn't generate as much aggro. in my previous guild, who's biggest accomplishment was Vindi, we had luck starting the rotation about 4 seconds late and having the paladins burn LoH in a rotation.<br />
hope this helps<br />
-Serrath<br />
60 cleric of <a href="http://www.tritonguild.com">Triton</a><br />
Povar server<br />
